---
import CourseLayout from "../../layouts/CourseLayout.astro";
import ExternalResource from "../../components/content/ExternalResource.astro";
import { courseMeta, getNavItemHref, rlCourseNav } from "../../data/rl-course-nav";
import { getFirstLessonSlug } from "../../lib/course";

const firstLesson = getFirstLessonSlug();
---

<CourseLayout title={courseMeta.title} description={courseMeta.description}>
  <div class="prose prose-lesson">
    <p>
      If you are here, you have probably already heard about reinforcement learning (RL) and are interested in learning more about it. 
    </p>
    <p>
      While this is a course, it does not cover the theory itself. 
      It relies on external resources for the theory (books, videos, papers, etc.) and provides supplementary material which you can use to build a deeper understanding of the subject. 
      This includes discussions, exercises, algorithm implementations, and interactive simulations.
      I created these resources to help me learn the subject myself, and I hope they can help you too.
    </p>
    <p>
      When learning a new subject, it is easy to race through the foundational material quickly.
      In my experience, the foundational topics seem quite simple and it is easy to think you have understood them while you really haven't.
      The lack of understanding and intuition becomes apparent when you move to more complex topics.
    </p>
    <p>
      I have found that it is easier to build a strong foundation by doing the following:
      <ul>
        <li>
          Spending time thinking about the concepts.
        </li>
        <li>
          Writing down and possibly deriving the formulas yourself.
        </li>
        <li>
          Implementing the algorithms and recreating the results you see in the literature.
        </li>
        <li>
          Building your own environments and playing around with the algorithms.
        </li>
        <li>
          Thinking ahead about what modifications are possible to the algorithms and how they could be useful.
        </li>
      </ul>
      The resources provided here are meant to help you do the above. Most of what I want to discuss is posed as a question or a thinking exercise.
    </p>
    <p>
      For each topic, I will link to external resources that you can use to learn the theory.
      Once you have read the theory, come back here and test your understanding with exercises and simulations.
      Move on to the next topic once you are ready.
    </p>
    <p>
      I will use Introduction to Reinforcement Learning by Sutton and Barto as the main textbook — the standard reference for RL theory and algorithms.
      The structure of this course will follow the structure of the book, so that you can easily switch between the two.
      The PDF version of the book is available for free.
    </p>

    <ExternalResource
      href="http://incompleteideas.net/book/the-book.html"
      title="Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction"
      description="Sutton & Barto — the standard reference for RL theory and algorithms."
      type="book"
    />

    <p>
      Another important aspect of this course is that I will lean heavily on AI to help us learn the subject.
      Hence, for thinking exercises and questions, I will link to AI so you can get any doubts cleared instantly.
      The links I provide will have the prompt with the full context so that AI can give you meaningful answers.
      For most of the questions, I will also include a (likely AI generated) answer if you prefer not having to ask AI.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you find the course useful, or if you would like to suggest improvements/corrections, please send me an email at <a href="mailto:hi@vaibhavsinha.me" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-(--color-accent)!">hi@vaibhavsinha.me</a>.
      I would love to hear from you!
    </p>

    {
      firstLesson && (
        <p class="pt-10">
          <a
            href={`/rl-course/${firstLesson}`}
            class="not-prose inline-block rounded border border-(--color-border) px-4 py-2 font-mono text-sm text-(--color-text) transition-colors hover:border-(--color-accent) hover:text-(--color-accent)"
          >
            Start with Introduction →
          </a>
        </p>
      )
    }

    <div class="not-prose mt-14 border-t border-(--color-border) pt-10">
      <h2 class="nav-section-label mb-6">Course outline</h2>
      {
        rlCourseNav.map((group) => (
          <div class="mb-8 last:mb-0">
            <h3 class="mb-3 font-sans text-base font-medium text-(--color-text-bright)">{group.section}</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-1">
              {group.items.map((item) => (
                <li>
                  <a
                    href={getNavItemHref(item.slug)}
                    class="nav-link text-[0.875rem]! text-(--color-prose)!"
                  >
                    {item.title}
                  </a>
                  {item.children && item.children.length > 0 && (
                    <ul class="nav-children">
                      {item.children.map((child) => (
                        <li>
                          <a
                            href={getNavItemHref(child.slug)}
                            class="nav-link"
                          >
                            {child.title}
                          </a>
                        </li>
                      ))}
                    </ul>
                  )}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </div>
</CourseLayout>
